Stellt euch eine sehr lange Webseite mit einer Menge Abschnitten vor (also eine HTML-Spezifikation auf einer Seite). Wenn der Nutzer einen bestimmten Abschnitt anfordert (z. B. page.html#section7), wie wäre es, wenn der Webserver diesen Abschnitt zuerst streamt und danach die anderen Abschnitte?
Streamreihenfolge:
1. Beginn des HTML-Dokuments bis
2. HTML für Abschnitt 7
3. HTML für Abschnitt 1, 2, 3 usw.
Then the browser would ensure that sections 1 to 6 are displayed *over* section 7 on the webpage.
Does that make sense? Would it be helpful?
The linked section (#section7) should be rendered as quickly as possible without having to implement elements with JavaScript. I just want a very long HTML document, but the linked sections should be rendered as quickly as possible. This should work with HTML.
The content could be streamed, and then the browser would insert all <contents> into the <div>.
<div id=sec1></div>
<div id=sec2></div>
usw.
<div id=sec7>section 7…</div>
<contents for=sec1>section 1…</contents>
<contents for=sec2>section 2…</contents>
...
It will not be streamed sequentially, but the browser will piece together the HTML document as if it was streamed sequentially.
@user22 You can also rearrange documents without using JS. You should not use the hash part of the URL if you want the server to do something, but you can use query string parameters so that the server knows which section you want first. When rearranging the parts, you have several options:
1. Use CSS
2. Use a template with sections
@user23 Yes. The issue is that the visual order (what the user sees) does not match the DOM order. It would be useful to have an HTML function that allows streaming out of order, but still arranges the content in the DOM order.
But the idea with slots looks promising. I'll give that a try.
@user22 Oh, do you want the browser to sort out the DOM order?
@user23 Yes, that's the idea. Section 7 would be streamed first so that the user can see it as soon as possible. If this could be done without affecting the DOM order, that would be great, then the browser would ensure that the resulting DOM order matches the visual order.
So Section 7 should be streamed first, but the final result should look as if all sections were streamed in order.
@user22 @user23 Check out PHOOOS without JS: https://github.com/niutech/phooos
